to leave a message about the wallet:\nTo me there are a few VERY important aspects that I look in a wallet.\nI usually buy the squareish wallet with a single fold. \n1. A place to attach a wallet chain would be really helpful. most leather wallet don't have this feature, I've only seen them on cloth wallet. So I usually either have to mod my wallet for it, but because I don't have a good enough way to attach it, so it usually significantly decreases the lifespan of the wallet.\n2. A windowed ID pouch would be really nice, but if the wallet were to have a windowed ID pouch, it needs to be made of mesh metal, never clear plastic.\n     The ink from your ID or what ever you put in that pouch will always rub off and end up stuck on the clear plastic.\n3. The card slot divider design\n     I've seen alot of card divide that's a single pouch with a few fabric divider with slips of leather on top. These are FKING AWFUL. when it comes time to put your card back in after using it. It often pushed these dividers down into the pouch and you have to fish it out. also they usually end up falling out after a bit of use.\n4. The material,\n    I really like leather wallet. I know that's a preference. I personally don't care if the leather is made from extracting self righteous hypocrisy or torture killing new born babies. But it needs to be durable and last a long time. But what I can't FKING stand is what they call \"genuine leather\".\n     You see this material everywhere these days. It's made of shredded leather glued together and pressed into shape. They are GAWD FKING AWFUL, they don't last, and will fall apart after a year or two. I have given vegan leather a try before. they degraded into a cardboard like material extremely quick, after that i've given up on that too.\n5. The zipper is useless, does nothing good. only wastes more time. unless it's on a pouch or something, never on the main compartment.\n\nThat's all I can think of right now. will add more if more comes to mind."},"publishedTime":"1 year the Mercedes stuff, I published a comment on the Facebook channel and everybody laughed at me. But people don't understand modern engines and powertrain components. \n\nTLDR: Power is not \"already there\" it's unleashed by different SW and brings extra wear. That wear requires additional warranty cost reserves. \n\nIn the case of newer engines (and EVs are similar), the physical parts are there but how they interact is controlled by software. Fuel injection (quantity and timing), valve timing, clutch engagement, can be controlled by software and 2 engines (one with 300 hp and other with 350 HP) can be physically same but with different calibrations the output is different. That performance It's not \"already there\" and you have not paid for it with the car. \n\nThat additional performance has additional wear and tear in some components (example, clutch) and some of those will have a reduced life because of that. To maintain the original terms of the warranty the OEM charges for the additional performance. \n\nI don't agree that this should be a subscription model, but a cost needs to be covered. The alternatives are already there: paying from the start additional price for additional power (more than the subscription cost) or going to the aftermarket scene to have a custom calibration but voiding your warranty. \n\nThis subscription model allows you to \"test\" how better acceleration feels. You might discover it's not that awesome or that the returns are little vs the cost (most people will find that their case). \n\nThis has been happening in commercial vehicles (heavy trucks) from more than 30 years (sw based power platforms) and over the air programming for about 5 years."},"publishedTime":"1 year ago
